    <header class="article-header">
      <p class="article-meta">Published March 20, 2026</p>
      <h1>Self-Employment Tax Guide 2026: Everything Freelancers Need to Know</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">One of the biggest shocks for new freelancers and contractors is discovering the self-employment tax. When you worked as an employee, your employer quietly paid half of your Social Security and Medicare taxes — you never saw it, never thought about it. Now, as a self-employed person, you pay both halves. That 15.3% on top of your regular income taxes can feel like a gut punch. But armed with the right knowledge, you can legally reduce this bill significantly through deductions, retirement contributions, and smart business structuring.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>What Is Self-Employment Tax?</h2>
    <p>Self-employment tax is the self-employed person's equivalent of FICA — the Social Security and Medicare taxes that every worker pays. The difference is how those taxes are split:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Employees:</strong> Pay 6.2% Social Security + 1.45% Medicare = 7.65% total. Their employer also pays 7.65% that the employee never sees.</li>
      <li><strong>Self-employed:</strong> Pay both halves — 12.4% Social Security + 2.9% Medicare = <strong>15.3% total</strong>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Self-employment tax is separate from federal income tax. You pay both. A freelancer with $80,000 in net income might owe roughly $11,300 in SE tax and $9,000 in federal income tax — a combined effective rate of about 25% before any deductions.</p>
    <p>Use our <a href="/tax-calculators/self-employment-tax-calculator/">self-employment tax calculator</a> to see your exact SE tax, income tax, and total federal tax bill.</p>

    <h2>The 92.35% Rule: Why SE Tax Is Not on 100% of Income</h2>
    <p>Here is a calculation detail that trips up even experienced freelancers: SE tax is not calculated on your full net self-employment income. It is calculated on <strong>92.35%</strong> of your net income.</p>
    <p>The formula: Net SE Income × 0.9235 × 15.3% = SE Tax</p>
    <p>Example: $80,000 net income × 0.9235 = $73,880. $73,880 × 0.153 = $11,304 SE tax.</p>
    <p>Why 92.35%? When employees pay 7.65% FICA, their employer pays the other 7.65% on a separate line item. The 92.35% adjustment (which is 1 minus 7.65%) puts self-employed people on roughly equal footing with employees for the purposes of calculating the Social Security and Medicare base.</p>

    <h2>Social Security Wage Base: $176,100 in 2026</h2>
    <p>The 12.4% Social Security portion of SE tax only applies up to the annual wage base — $176,100 in 2026. Income above this threshold is still subject to the 2.9% Medicare tax, but not the Social Security portion. This means:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>SE income up to $176,100: taxed at 15.3%</li>
      <li>SE income above $176,100: taxed at 2.9% (Medicare only)</li>
      <li>SE income above $200,000 (single) / $250,000 (MFJ): additional 0.9% Medicare surtax</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The wage base increases each year with inflation. For high earners, this cap provides some relief — the effective SE tax rate on $300,000 of income is meaningfully lower than on $100,000.</p>

    <h2>The SE Tax Deduction: Deduct Half of What You Pay</h2>
    <p>One of the most valuable tax benefits for the self-employed is often overlooked: you can deduct half of your SE tax as an above-the-line deduction. This deduction:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Does not require itemizing</li>
      <li>Reduces your adjusted gross income (AGI) directly</li>
      <li>In turn lowers your federal income tax bill</li>
      <li>Is automatically calculated on Schedule SE</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Example: $11,304 SE tax × 50% = $5,652 deduction. If you are in the 22% bracket, this saves you $1,243 in income taxes on top of the SE tax you already paid. This deduction mimics the employer-side: employees never paid income tax on the employer's 7.65% FICA contribution, so self-employed people get a comparable above-the-line deduction.</p>

    <h2>Business Deductions That Reduce SE Tax</h2>
    <p>Every legitimate business expense you deduct reduces your net SE income, which reduces both your SE tax and income tax. Because SE tax is 15.3%, each dollar of business deduction saves you 15.3 cents in SE tax plus your marginal income tax rate. A freelancer in the 22% bracket saves 37.3 cents in total federal tax for every dollar of legitimate business deduction.</p>
    <p><strong>Key deductible expenses:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Home office (dedicated workspace used regularly and exclusively for business)</li>
      <li>Business internet and phone (business-use percentage)</li>
      <li>Equipment: computers, monitors, cameras, microphones</li>
      <li>Software subscriptions and professional tools</li>
      <li>Professional development: courses, certifications, books, conferences</li>
      <li>Professional services: accountant, lawyer fees for business matters</li>
      <li>Business travel and mileage (70 cents/mile in 2026)</li>
      <li>Business meals with clients (50% deductible)</li>
      <li>Marketing and advertising costs</li>
      <li>Bank fees and payment processing fees for business accounts</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Self-Employed Health Insurance Deduction</h2>
    <p>If you pay for your own health, dental, and vision insurance — and are not eligible for employer-sponsored coverage through a spouse — you can deduct 100% of your premiums as an above-the-line deduction. This includes coverage for yourself, your spouse, and your dependents.</p>
    <p>This deduction reduces your AGI (and therefore your income tax), but it does not reduce your SE tax base. Still, for someone paying $6,000/year in premiums in the 22% bracket, this is a $1,320 annual income tax savings.</p>

    <h2>Retirement Contributions: The Most Powerful SE Tax Strategy</h2>
    <p>Self-employed retirement accounts let you shelter a large portion of income from taxes — in some cases more than employees can. The 2026 contribution limits are generous:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Solo 401(k):</strong> Up to $23,500 as employee deferrals + up to 25% of net SE income as employer contributions, maximum combined $70,000. If you are 50+, add a $7,500 catch-up. This is the most powerful option for high-income self-employed people.</li>
      <li><strong>SEP-IRA:</strong> Contribute up to 25% of net SE income (after the SE deduction), maximum $70,000. Simpler to set up than a Solo 401(k).</li>
      <li><strong>SIMPLE IRA:</strong> Employee deferrals up to $16,500 + mandatory employer match. Better for self-employed people with employees.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Retirement contributions reduce your income tax but do not reduce your SE tax base. However, for most self-employed people, the income tax savings alone justify maximizing these contributions. A SEP-IRA contribution of $20,000 at a 22% bracket saves $4,400 in income taxes — while building your retirement nest egg.</p>

    <h2>Quarterly Estimated Tax Payments</h2>
    <p>As a self-employed person, no employer withholds taxes from your income. You are responsible for paying taxes quarterly. Miss these payments and the IRS charges an underpayment penalty.</p>
    <p><strong>2026 quarterly due dates:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Q1 (Jan–Mar income): April 15, 2026</li>
      <li>Q2 (Apr–May income): June 16, 2026</li>
      <li>Q3 (Jun–Aug income): September 15, 2026</li>
      <li>Q4 (Sep–Dec income): January 15, 2027</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Safe harbor rule:</strong> You avoid the underpayment penalty if your total payments equal at least 90% of your current-year tax liability, OR 100% of last year's tax liability (110% if your prior-year AGI exceeded $150,000). For freelancers with volatile income, the prior-year safe harbor is often the easiest to calculate.</p>
    <p><strong>How much to set aside:</strong> A common rule of thumb for most freelancers is 25–30% of every payment received. This covers both SE tax and income tax for typical income levels. Higher earners may need to set aside 35–40%.</p>
    <p>Pay quarterly estimates through IRS Direct Pay, Electronic Federal Tax Payment System (EFTPS), or by mailing Form 1040-ES with a check. EFTPS is free and the most reliable method.</p>

    <h2>When Does Forming an S-Corp Make Sense?</h2>
    <p>At higher income levels, some freelancers and small business owners elect S-Corporation status to reduce SE tax. Here is how it works: instead of paying SE tax on all your profit, you pay yourself a "reasonable salary" (subject to payroll taxes at the same 15.3% rate) and take the remaining profit as a distribution (not subject to SE tax).</p>
    <p>Example: $150,000 net profit. As a sole proprietor: SE tax on all $150,000. As an S-Corp: $80,000 salary (reasonable for your role) → SE tax on $80,000. $70,000 as a distribution → no SE tax. Potential SE tax savings: roughly $10,710 annually.</p>
    <p>However, S-Corp status adds complexity: payroll tax filings, separate business bank accounts, annual S-Corp tax returns, and potentially higher accounting fees. The math typically makes sense above $80,000–$100,000 in annual net profit. Consult a CPA before making this election.</p>

